05244nam a2200697Ia 9789633861523DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20172017hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9789633861523  a(DE-B1597)633437  a(OCoLC)1338019105  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aDJK51b.O35 2017 7aPOL0050002bisacsh04a949.6/0407222300aOf Red Dragons and Evil Spirits :bPost-Communist Historiography between Democratization and the New Politics of History /ced. by Oto Luthar. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. “Red Dragon and the Evil Spirits” -- t1. On the (In)convertibility of National Memory into European Legitimacy: The Bulgarian Case -- t2. Equalizing Jesus’s, Jewish, and Croat Suffering—Post-Socialist Politics of History in Croatia -- t3 Wars of Memory in Post-Communist Romania -- t4. Reflections on the Principles of the Critical Culture of Memory -- t5. The Struggle for Legitimacy: Constructing the National History of Slovakia After 1989 -- t6. Victims and Traditions: Narratives of Hungarian National History After the Age of Extremes -- t7. Instrumentalization of History in Bosnia and Herzegovina -- t8. Post-Socialist Historiography Between Democratization and New Exclusivist Politics of History -- tAuthors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe collection of well-researched essays assesses the uses and misuses of history 25 years after the collapse of Soviet hegemony in Eastern Europe. As opposed to the revival of national histories that seemed to be the prevailing historiographical approach of the 1990s, the last decade has seen a particular set of narratives equating Nazism and Communism. This provides opportunities to exonerate wartime collaboration, casting the nation as victim even when its government was allied with Germany. While the Jewish Holocaust is acknowledged, its meaning and significance are obfuscated. In their comparative analysis the authors are also interested in new practices of ‘Europeanness’. Therefore their presentations of Slovak, Hungarian, Romanian, Bulgarian, Serbian, Bosnian, Croatian and Slovenian post-communist memory politics move beyond the common national myths in order to provide a new insight into transnational interactions and exchanges in Europe in general. The juxtaposition of these politics, the processes in other parts of Europe, the modes of remembering shaped by displacement and the transnational enable a close encounter with the divergences and assess the potential of the formation of common, European memory practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHistoriographyzEurope, Eastern. 0aPost-communismzEurope, EasternxHistoriography. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  a21st century, Bosnia, Memory politics, Post-communism, Romania, Slovakia, Slovenia.1 aFilandra, Šaćir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoleva, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuljić, Todor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaczó, Ferenc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuthar, Oto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuthar, Oto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMichela, Miroslav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadonić, Ljiljana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShafir, Michael, econt